chapters.title: <Untitled Chapter 1>
“Is Climate Change Real?” YouTube video on Bill Whittle channel - https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=v_RuverrEZ4&t=80s
Thermal expansion of oceans at https://earthobservatory.nasa.gov/Features/OceanCooling/page5.php
"Kinematic Constraints on Glacier Contributions to 21st-Century Sea-Level Rise" --  WT Pfeffer et al., Science 2008
"A Semi-Empirical Approach to Projecting Future Sea-Level Rise"
“Reconstructing sea level from paleo and projected temperatures 200 to 2100AD”
“Global sea level rise scenarios for the United States National Climate Assessment”
“Contribution of Antarctica to past and future sea level rise”
Bill Nye climate video.
“The Phanerozoic record of global sea level change”
“An atmospheric pCO2 reconstruction across the Cretaceous-Tertiary boundary from leaf megafossils”
Whittle doesn’t give a source for this reconstruction, but it seems to be Mann, Bradley and Hughes 1998
Whittle also doesn’t give a source for this graph, but I tracked down the author as Humlum at Oslo University. It hasn’t been published or peer-reviewed, it’s just being passed round the blogosphere.
5:18 – CORRECTION: The Arrhenius paper was 1896, not 1894. Other than that, the titles, authors and dates of these papers are ALL shown very clearly in the video.
1950 as baseline: http://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/10.1029/96JC03837/epdf
GISP2 raw data from:
Ibid.
“A Reconstruction of Regional and Global Temperature for the Past 11,300 years.” --  Markott at al. , Science 2013
"CO2 as a primary driver of Phanerozoic climate" -- D. Royer et al, GSA Today, March 2004. Based on Geocarb III data from:
“Time-specific black mudstones and global hyperwarming on the
Solar output graph from James Imamura, University of Oregon Dept of physics
“Climate Sensitivity during the Phanerozoic: Lessons for the Future”
"Geocarb III: A revised model of atmospheric CO2 over Phanerozoic time" -- R. Berner and Z. Kothavala, American Journal of Science, Feb 2001
"CO2 as a primary driver of Phanerozoic climate" -- D. Royer et al, GSA Today, March 2004.
“Large Perturbations of the Carbon Cycle During Recovery from the End-Permian Extinction” – Payne, Science 2004
“δ13Corg chemostratigraphy of the Permian‐Triassic boundary in the Maitai Group, New Zealand: Evidence for high‐latitudinal methane release”
“Volatile fluxes during flood basalt eruptions and potential effects on the global environment: A Deccan perspective”
"Timing of Atmospheric CO2 and Antarctic Temperature Changes Across Termination III" --
A list of the various myths and where I address them can be found in the video description of my video “The evidence for global warming without computer models or the IPCC.”
